metadata.description:
Just an ordinary scene from a typical day, working as a Sprocket Factory engineer. Inspiration for this work is drawn from the composable nature of blockchain smart contracts and the flow of value between networks of autonomous machines and free-willed individuals.

metadata.name: On the sea, I ... #329
metadata.description:
Generative painting based on churning waves with floating buoys. Represented in three different media.

Features:
- Three drawing styles: "watercolor" 70%, "brush" 30%, or "block" 70%
- Warm white or blue waves
- Variable border and column sizes
- Number of columns
- Calm waves at the edges or center
- Color 80% or red 20% buoys
- Buoy drawing style, "watercolor" or "brush"

Viewing in desktop Chrome is recommended for the best results.
Press ’s’ to save a screenshot. Image size is 928x1200px
Press ’p’ to pause/resume.

Add '&size=#' to the end of the live view URL to render a variation of your edition at a resolution up to 3,000 px.

metadata.name: Anachronous #248
metadata.description:
This project is about the exploration of chaotic structures created with lines and blurry silhouettes. They work together to make the shapes emerge without revealing them completely and create dark and light areas that compose a feeling of depth and weight to the scene.

Some pieces are chaotic, some more ordered. Some have strong compositions, some don't. By zooming in on the details we can let our mind wander and start seeing shapes.

Best experienced in full-screen.

Press S to take a screenshot
Press M to take a high resolution screenshot
Press H to take a higher resolution screenshot (may not work for some devices)

WARNING: Project is using webgl, it may not work on some older devices.

Original artwork by William Watkins · Lyon, 2022

metadata.name: Mur #246
metadata.description:
Mur is a series of computational drawings of stacked and falling bricks. The bricks are placed in different configurations of walls, towers, stacks and paths, and are then exposed to gravity. 

The graphics are coded with p5.js and the rigid body simulations with ammo.js. In live mode, press 's' to save a screenshot and 'e' to save a high resolution image. Press 't' to toggle textures. 

Each scene is drawn twice, first brick by brick as they fall or stay in place, then the scene as a whole. Mur is optimized for Chrome, uses WebGL and may not work in all browsers.

metadata.name: Alienpillars #109
metadata.description:
"A rare type of bug that supposedly arrived on a cargo ship is destroying crops on planet Uctumi, in the binary system of Extronium. A wide variety of very resistant subspecies has mutated and it is necessary to study and identify all of them to obtain a gen-activated pesticide that will work on all of their variations. The pest department of the Uctumi central government is working hard on it, and they say that these strange critters are probably related to similar species that inhabited the planet Earth of the Solar system a long time ago and have spread over the galaxy."

My second piece using the p5.js raymarcher I wrote. The drawing is made of circles and lines based on the 3D data. I wanted to try something hairy as it's easy to draw lines aligned to the surface normal with this method. I also used a shader for the frame and the glitchy/sketch features.

Features 

body color: green-red-purple-yellow-blue-black
body tone: dark-light
spots color: orange-green-blue-yellow-white
hair tips: yes-no
hair #1: short-medium-long
hair #2: short-medium-long
head size: small-medium-large
head shape: long-spherical-wide
glitchy mode: 10% chance
sketch mode: 9% chance

metadata.name: Sneronoi #151
metadata.description:
Stochastic neighbor embedding meets Voronoi tessellation.

Images are generated by gradient descent and the optimization process is shown as an animation. Each piece is considered final when the animation stops. There are 11 different color palettes and two distinct input point arrangements, allowing for a wide range of distinct visual outputs. Made with D3.

Press 's' to save as svg.

Press 'p' to save as png (4000x4000).

Author:
Claus O. Wilke
https://clauswilke.com/art
https://twitter.com/clauswilke

metadata.name: Mystic Paradise #36
metadata.description:
Generate your own mystic paradise. 
Here is generative pieces creating an animated skyline with a reflection .

The size, position and frequency of shapes are generated for each token, along with the color theme.  

Movements and positions are generated by a noise and a seed, it’s the same for each view.
 On live version the visual fit your screen. There is also an export menu if you press 'm' or 'e' on the live version.

Shortcuts :
    - click to play/pause the animation
    - press ‘f’ to launch the fullscreen mode
    - On live version : press ‘e’ or ‘m’ to open the export menu
    - On live version : press ‘h’ to hide the cursor

Features :
    - Number of shapes - between 50 and 310
    - Reflection type - « mirror » or « continu » 
    - Infinite reflection - true or false
    - Direction - « west » & « east » give an isometric rendering, or « straight » 
    - Length Factor is a value to manage the animated distance of each shape linked with the noise
    - Particles count - between 200 & 600
    - Visible Aura - true or false 

Created by Quentin Hocdé, in Brussels (Belgium).

metadata.name: Ambiguous Instances #36
metadata.description:
“Ambiguous Instances” is the sixth collection released as a part of NeoMent's "Abandoned Reality" series.

Often people use a specific example to argue their point of view. Unfortunately, this means that they can completely make it up or hyperbolise it to benefit their views, which means that it's a completely invalid argument.

Statistics, on the other hand, cannot lie, since they are just pure observations.
That is unless they are completely made up, of course.

metadata.name: Qubitscape #223
metadata.description:
Qubitscape is my painterly approach to a flowfields with colors and circular shape modifier. There are 12 color palettes and 10 visual output styles. 

"Animated" style has 10% probability

"Wildcard Rainbow" style is the of the styles with %5 probability and wide range of parameters

In a Qubitscape there is always a probability of anomalies by color or by pattern. Look out for them! 

For more information check out : https://www.muratatimtay.com

Created with p5js. 
Creation Date: 12/17/2021
Murat Atimtay

metadata.name: Bellissimas #51
metadata.description:
Expressive portraits inspired by @michelepetrelli 

The used techniques search in the unexplored field of mixing pfp layer based work and real-time generative algorithms changing and adding to the premade assets.

The pre-generated assets include original artworks by Petrelli, Imitations of Petrelli's work by @brutalisti, GAN generated artworks inspired by Petrelli using several different AI technologies.

Every generatively chosen layer combination is live-processed and generatively altered in aspects of color and shape. Then the generative algorithm proceed with captured color palettes and generate background and additional drawing over and under the initial layers. The final result as acquired by visualizing everything with live generative algorithm that give additional layer of uniqueness.

Project by  @michelepetrelli & @brutalisti, curated by XCOLLABS

metadata.name: Sabler #24
metadata.description:
'Sabler', an anagram of 'Albers', is a generative homage to the work of the Bauhaus textile artist Anni Albers.

The aesthetic of this piece and its proportions are guided by the Golden Ratio (1.618 : 1) and as such, each part of the composition relates in some way to its larger self. 

As lines playfully extend and overlap one another from various grid segments, patterns appear, 'ghost' shadings emerge and complexity is implied even with the use of very simple elements. In line with that simplicity, colors and palettes have also been kept to a minimum.

There are no rarities or special features, other than for you to enjoy the unique qualities of your piece!

You can save a high resolution 3000px x 3000px PNG of your edition by pressing the 'S' key.
